inference:
Let the radius of the circle be $r$.  The side length of the smaller hexagon is equal to the radius of the circle, $r$, since the hexagon is inscribed in the circle.  The side length of the larger hexagon is equal to the diameter of the circle, $2r$, since the hexagon is circumscribed about the circle.

[asy]
unitsize(1 cm);

pair A, B, C, D, E, F, O;

O = (0,0);
A = dir(0);
B = dir(60);
C = dir(120);
D = dir(180);
E = dir(240);
F = dir(300);

draw(Circle(O,1));
draw(A--B--C--D--E--F--cycle);
draw(O--A);
draw(O--B);

label("$r$", (O + A)/2, SE);
label("$r$", (O + B)/2, NE);
label("$2r$", (A + B)/2, NW);

dot("$A$", A, SE);
dot("$B$", B, NE);
dot("$C$", C, NW);
dot("$D$", D, SW);
dot("$E$", E, S);
dot("$F$", F, SE);
dot("$O$", O, S);
[/asy]

The area of an equilateral triangle with side length $s$ is $\frac{\sqrt{3}}{4} s^2$.  A regular hexagon can be divided into 6 equilateral triangles, so the area of a regular hexagon with side length $s$ is $6 \cdot \frac{\sqrt{3}}{4} s^2 = \frac{3 \sqrt{3}}{2} s^2$.

The area of the smaller hexagon is $\frac{3 \sqrt{3}}{2} r^2$, and the area of the larger hexagon is $\frac{3 \sqrt{3}}{2} (2r)^2 = 6 \sqrt{3} r^2$.  The ratio of the area of the larger hexagon to the area of the smaller hexagon is $\frac{6 \sqrt{3} r^2}{\frac{3 \sqrt{3}}{2} r^2} = \boxed{\frac{4}{1}}$.

ground_truth:
Form a triangle whose first vertex is the center of the circle and whose other two vertices are the midpoint and one of the endpoints of a side of the larger hexagon, as shown in the diagram.  Since each interior angle of a regular hexagon is 120 degrees, this triangle is a 30-60-90 right triangle.  Let $r$ be the radius of the circle.  The length of the longer leg of the triangle is $r$, so the length of the shorter leg is $r/\sqrt{3}$ and the length of the hypotenuse is $2r/\sqrt{3}$.  Since for the smaller hexagon the length of the segment connecting a vertex to the center is $r$, the dimensions of the larger hexagon are $2/\sqrt{3}$ times larger than the dimensions of the smaller hexagon.  Therefore, the area of the larger triangle is $(2/\sqrt{3})^2=\boxed{\frac{4}{3}}$ times greater than the area of the smaller triangle.

[asy]
size(5cm);
defaultpen(linewidth(.7pt)+fontsize(8pt));
dotfactor=4;
int i;
draw(circle((0,0),1));
for(i=0;i<=5;++i)

{

draw(dir(60*i)--dir(60*(i+1)));

draw(2/sqrt(3)*dir(60*i)--2/sqrt(3)*dir(60*(i+1)));

}
draw(2/sqrt(3)*dir(0)--(0,0)--dir(30));
draw(0.93*dir(30)--dir(30)+0.07*dir(-60)+0.07*dir(210)--dir(30)+0.07*dir(-60));[/asy]

